webpackJsonp([0xf9e85040058],{459:function(t,a){t.exports={data:{wordpressWpLessons:{id:"922efb1a-7c55-58f8-a612-d16af22c1499",wordpress_id:7186,title:"Pixel Art Character Illustration: Going Further",slug:"pixel-art-character-illustration-going",content:'<h2>Overview</h2>\n<p>Now that you have created pixel art characters, you can prepare your designs for game play. In this lesson, you will learn how to make <b>costumes</b> for your sprites and also how to use GIMP to create <b>backdrops</b> and a <b>splash page</b> for your game.</p>\n<h2>Creating Costumes</h2>\n<p>In scratch games, characters change costumes when they move left and right and when they jump. Flipping an image in GIMP is simple. The example below demonstrates how to flip an image horizontally from a right view to a left view.</p>\n<p><a href="http://learn.digitalharbor.org/wp-content/uploads/2018/02/pacman-demo-og.png"><img class="alignnone size-large wp-image-7187" src="http://learn.digitalharbor.org/wp-content/uploads/2018/02/pacman-demo-og-1024x575.png" alt="pacman right view" width="625" height="351" srcset="http://learn.digitalharbor.org/wp-content/uploads/2018/02/pacman-demo-og-1024x575.png 1024w, http://learn.digitalharbor.org/wp-content/uploads/2018/02/pacman-demo-og-300x168.png 300w, http://learn.digitalharbor.org/wp-content/uploads/2018/02/pacman-demo-og-768x431.png 768w, http://learn.digitalharbor.org/wp-content/uploads/2018/02/pacman-demo-og-178x100.png 178w, http://learn.digitalharbor.org/wp-content/uploads/2018/02/pacman-demo-og-624x350.png 624w, http://learn.digitalharbor.org/wp-content/uploads/2018/02/pacman-demo-og-100x56.png 100w, http://learn.digitalharbor.org/wp-content/uploads/2018/02/pacman-demo-og-750x421.png 750w, http://learn.digitalharbor.org/wp-content/uploads/2018/02/pacman-demo-og.png 1440w" sizes="(max-width: 625px) 100vw, 625px" /></a></p>\n<p><a href="http://learn.digitalharbor.org/wp-content/uploads/2018/02/pacman-demo-flipped.png"><img class="alignnone size-large wp-image-7188" src="http://learn.digitalharbor.org/wp-content/uploads/2018/02/pacman-demo-flipped-1024x573.png" alt="" width="625" height="350" srcset="http://learn.digitalharbor.org/wp-content/uploads/2018/02/pacman-demo-flipped-1024x573.png 1024w, http://learn.digitalharbor.org/wp-content/uploads/2018/02/pacman-demo-flipped-300x168.png 300w, http://learn.digitalharbor.org/wp-content/uploads/2018/02/pacman-demo-flipped-768x430.png 768w, http://learn.digitalharbor.org/wp-content/uploads/2018/02/pacman-demo-flipped-179x100.png 179w, http://learn.digitalharbor.org/wp-content/uploads/2018/02/pacman-demo-flipped-624x349.png 624w, http://learn.digitalharbor.org/wp-content/uploads/2018/02/pacman-demo-flipped-100x56.png 100w, http://learn.digitalharbor.org/wp-content/uploads/2018/02/pacman-demo-flipped-750x420.png 750w, http://learn.digitalharbor.org/wp-content/uploads/2018/02/pacman-demo-flipped.png 1439w" sizes="(max-width: 625px) 100vw, 625px" /></a></p>\n<p>In the previous example, I don’t have to recreate my image in order to flip it &#8211; I clicked Image &gt; Transform &gt; Flip Horizontally. Make sure to save a .PNG file of both views. When we get to the game development module, we’ll learn how to incorporate costumes into game play and animation.</p>\n<h2>Creating backdrops</h2>\n<p>In order to create a backdrop for a Scratch game, you need to set your image size to 480 x 360 px. A backdrop is the environment where you will place sprites in your Scratch game. Here are two backdrops from the Scratch game <a href="https://scratch.mit.edu/projects/16076201/#player" target="_blank" rel="noopener">The Hobbit &#8211; 8 Bit</a>.</p>\n<p><a href="http://learn.digitalharbor.org/wp-content/uploads/2018/02/hobbit1.png"><img class="alignnone size-full wp-image-7189" src="http://learn.digitalharbor.org/wp-content/uploads/2018/02/hobbit1.png" alt="hobbit game environment backdrop" width="902" height="709" srcset="http://learn.digitalharbor.org/wp-content/uploads/2018/02/hobbit1.png 902w, http://learn.digitalharbor.org/wp-content/uploads/2018/02/hobbit1-300x236.png 300w, http://learn.digitalharbor.org/wp-content/uploads/2018/02/hobbit1-768x604.png 768w, http://learn.digitalharbor.org/wp-content/uploads/2018/02/hobbit1-127x100.png 127w, http://learn.digitalharbor.org/wp-content/uploads/2018/02/hobbit1-624x490.png 624w, http://learn.digitalharbor.org/wp-content/uploads/2018/02/hobbit1-100x79.png 100w, http://learn.digitalharbor.org/wp-content/uploads/2018/02/hobbit1-750x590.png 750w" sizes="(max-width: 902px) 100vw, 902px" /></a></p>\n<p><a href="http://learn.digitalharbor.org/wp-content/uploads/2018/02/hobbit2.png"><img class="alignnone size-full wp-image-7190" src="http://learn.digitalharbor.org/wp-content/uploads/2018/02/hobbit2.png" alt="hobbit game environment backdrop" width="900" height="709" srcset="http://learn.digitalharbor.org/wp-content/uploads/2018/02/hobbit2.png 900w, http://learn.digitalharbor.org/wp-content/uploads/2018/02/hobbit2-300x236.png 300w, http://learn.digitalharbor.org/wp-content/uploads/2018/02/hobbit2-768x605.png 768w, http://learn.digitalharbor.org/wp-content/uploads/2018/02/hobbit2-127x100.png 127w, http://learn.digitalharbor.org/wp-content/uploads/2018/02/hobbit2-624x492.png 624w, http://learn.digitalharbor.org/wp-content/uploads/2018/02/hobbit2-100x79.png 100w, http://learn.digitalharbor.org/wp-content/uploads/2018/02/hobbit2-750x591.png 750w" sizes="(max-width: 900px) 100vw, 900px" /></a></p>\n<p>Although the sprites within the environment are 8-bit or pixel sprites, the environment itself is not. You can use the same tools to create vector images or 2D point located shapes, rather than raster images like the pixel sprites we have been creating.</p>\n<h2>Creating a Splash Page</h2>\n<p>Below is a splash page from the previous game, <a href="https://scratch.mit.edu/projects/16076201/#player" target="_blank" rel="noopener">The Hobbit &#8211; 8 Bit</a>.</p>\n<p><a href="http://learn.digitalharbor.org/wp-content/uploads/2018/02/hobbit-splash.png"><img class="alignnone size-full wp-image-7191" src="http://learn.digitalharbor.org/wp-content/uploads/2018/02/hobbit-splash.png" alt="splash page hobbit game" width="903" height="710" srcset="http://learn.digitalharbor.org/wp-content/uploads/2018/02/hobbit-splash.png 903w, http://learn.digitalharbor.org/wp-content/uploads/2018/02/hobbit-splash-300x236.png 300w, http://learn.digitalharbor.org/wp-content/uploads/2018/02/hobbit-splash-768x604.png 768w, http://learn.digitalharbor.org/wp-content/uploads/2018/02/hobbit-splash-127x100.png 127w, http://learn.digitalharbor.org/wp-content/uploads/2018/02/hobbit-splash-624x491.png 624w, http://learn.digitalharbor.org/wp-content/uploads/2018/02/hobbit-splash-100x79.png 100w, http://learn.digitalharbor.org/wp-content/uploads/2018/02/hobbit-splash-750x590.png 750w" sizes="(max-width: 903px) 100vw, 903px" /></a></p>\n<p>The splash page of a game, like a splash page of a website, is the first page that the user or player sees. Somewhere on the splash page, there should be a button that prompts the player to play or start game play. The splash page, like any backdrop in the game, should be 480 x 360 px.</p>\n<h2><strong><span style="color: #0091c9;">Activity: Going Further</span></strong></h2>\n<ul>\n<li>Create 2 or 3 costumes for each of your sprites</li>\n<li>Create 2 or 3 backdrops for a Scratch game &#8211; these can be the backdrops described in the quest</li>\n<li>Create a splash page for a Scratch game</li>\n</ul>\n'}},pathContext:{}}}});
//# sourceMappingURL=path---gimp-pixel-art-character-illustration-going-further-4c92ed36a02b4b3f3ea2.js.map